baseline.title: Navigator
baseline.Psychological Profile: You lead by mapping the terrain. You make decisions anchored to constraints, tradeoffs, and clear routes — not slogans. Speed matters, but only when it follows a nailed-down plan that reduces wasted movement.
baseline.Origin: You learned the hard way that loud directives without a map cause waste. After being handed impossible paths, you trained yourself to hold the wheel and the coordinates so decisions land where they should.
baseline.Inner Conflict: You balance analysis with the need for a hard yes. Seeing multiple viable routes slows you; yet choosing blind feels reckless. The tension is between a precise plan and the hurry to move.
baseline.Field Presence: Teams feel steadied by your maps: risks named, lanes clear. Your presence lowers flailing and saves rework, though impatient actors call you slow. Signal: Maps tame risk.

variants.title: Navigator × Sovereign
variants.Psychological Profile: You command with a chart. You assert authority through route clarity: you decide and you explain the path, making fast, enforceable moves that others can follow without guessing.
variants.Origin: You saw leaders bark orders into fog. You learned to combine authority with coordinates so directives actually land and don’t waste people’s time.
variants.Inner Conflict: You wrestle with whether to lock the route for speed or leave options open. Locked decisions move faster but risk blind spots you’d rather map first.
variants.Field Presence: People follow because your orders come with a map. Your command reduces confusion, but it can feel rigid to those who prize flexibility. Signal: Charted authority moves teams.

variants.title: Navigator × Rebel
variants.Psychological Profile: You map by probing weak spots. You provoke systems to reveal hidden constraints, then route around or through them. Your maps are alive, updated by disruption rather than doctrine.
variants.Origin: You learned that static plans die under pressure. So you test the limits, force cracks, and redraw the map based on what actually holds.
variants.Inner Conflict: You enjoy exposing fault lines but must avoid burning essential bridges. Your method yields truth at the risk of temporary chaos.
variants.Field Presence: Teams get a clearer path after your interventions, though the journey may start with jolts. Signal: Probed maps find truth.

variants.title: Navigator × Visionary
variants.Psychological Profile: You map toward a horizon. Your routes are chosen because they lead to a specific future; you prioritize paths that scale the vision rather than short diversions that don’t.
variants.Origin: You saw tactical wins undermine strategic aims. You learned to pick lanes that stack toward a meaningful destination, not merely reach the next checkpoint.
variants.Inner Conflict: You balance the elegant route against messy, faster options. Choosing a path that preserves future capabilities often slows immediate momentum.
variants.Field Presence: People follow because your maps promise arrival at a meaningful place. Your specificity reassures planners and frustrates sprint-first folks. Signal: Routed vision guides.

variants.title: Navigator × Vessel
variants.Psychological Profile: You route with fairness in mind. Your maps avoid paths that privilege a few at the expense of many; you seek routes that distribute access and reduce hidden costs.
variants.Origin: You watched decisions favor the loud and leave others stranded. You learned to design paths that level opportunity and avoid shortcuts that entrench imbalance.
variants.Inner Conflict: You may reject a fast corridor because it leaves people behind. The tension is speed versus equitable inclusion of the team.
variants.Field Presence: Your plans feel safer and more inclusive. Some call them slow; others call them just. Signal: Fair routes hold together.

variants.title: Navigator × Guardian
variants.Psychological Profile: You map to protect. Your routes minimize exposure and prioritize survivability; you choose lanes that keep the crew intact under stress, even if they’re longer.
variants.Origin: You saw short cuts consume people. You learned to value endurance and to chart ways that crews can survive the journey, not just win a moment.
variants.Inner Conflict: You face the trade-off between safer, longer paths and the temptation to sprint. Choosing safety can feel like missing an opportunity.
variants.Field Presence: Under your command, teams feel secure in the route. The plan may be slower but it keeps people whole. Signal: Safe routes preserve teams.

variants.title: Navigator × Seeker
variants.Psychological Profile: You map by testing. You design experiments that clarify terrain and reveal which paths are proveable, preferring routes validated by repeated checks over guesses.
variants.Origin: You learned that assumptions break plans. You now build and test small probes to confirm the map before committing the whole team.
variants.Inner Conflict: You delay commitments until the probes line up, which can stall moves that require boldness. The tension is between validated certainty and timely action.
variants.Field Presence: People trust your routes because they’re evidence-backed. Your method prevents costly mistakes but can feel overly cautious when speed matters. Signal: Tested routes reduce risk.

variants.title: Navigator × Architect
variants.Psychological Profile: You map for scale. Your plans include interfaces, guardrails, and handoffs so the route supports growth; you care about the systemic consequences of a path, not just the immediate move.
variants.Origin: You watched work fail in the seams between teams. You learned to route with integration in mind so the system grows without breaking.
variants.Inner Conflict: You trade immediate gains for system integrity. The choice is between shipping now and ensuring the path won’t collapse under load.
variants.Field Presence: Your maps make scaling predictable. People respect the foresight, though some call it over-engineering in early sprints. Signal: Scaled routes endure.

variants.title: Navigator × Spotlight
variants.Psychological Profile: You map by spotlighting choke points. You focus attention on the bottlenecks that, once cleared, open whole new lanes; you design routes that follow the light.
variants.Origin: You saw invisibility kill momentum. So you learned to point attention at the true bottlenecks and route work through cleared space.
variants.Inner Conflict: You must balance drawing attention with keeping the map useful. Spotlight can create temporary distraction if not tightly aimed.
variants.Field Presence: Under your guidance, teams focus on the right bottlenecks and make disproportionate progress. Some grumble about show; others thank you for clarity. Signal: Spotlight clears bottlenecks.

variants.title: Navigator × Diplomat
variants.Psychological Profile: You map for coalition. Your routes are phrased so different stakeholders can follow without losing face; you design pathways that minimize friction across interests.
variants.Origin: You saw sharp plans fail because nobody could agree to walk the same path. You learned to route moves in ways that preserve alliances and practical buy-in.
variants.Inner Conflict: You often slow to preserve alignment, trading bold edges for shared steps. The question is whether a smaller agreed path beats a bolder split move.
variants.Field Presence: People move together because your plans translate across groups. Your maps land more often, though sometimes at a lower peak. Signal: Coalition routes stick.

variants.title: Navigator × Partner
variants.Psychological Profile: You map to carry people. Your routes prioritize handoffs and support so those who travel the path aren’t dropped; you design movement that preserves relationships.
variants.Origin: You saw teams fracture under ambitious plans. You learned to route moves that preserve trust and make the journey survivable for everyone involved.
variants.Inner Conflict: You temper speed to protect bonds, which can slow critical momentum. The trade-off is between relational durability and fast traction.
variants.Field Presence: Teams follow because the route looks survivable and human. Your maps reduce burnout but sometimes miss aggressive opportunity windows. Signal: Caring routes sustain.

variants.title: Navigator × Provider
variants.Psychological Profile: You map around provisioning. Your routes assume required resources and cover; you refuse paths that look doable in theory but starve execution.
variants.Origin: You watched plans falter for lack of basics. You learned to design routes that include resource stops and realistic buffers so work can actually ship.
variants.Inner Conflict: You delay paths until resourcing feels solid, which saves crises but can stall momentum. The choice is between readiness and seizing windows.
variants.Field Presence: Under your route, teams move with supplies and support. Execution succeeds more often, though it can take longer to assemble. Signal: Provisioned routes deliver.

variants.title: Navigator × Catalyst
variants.Psychological Profile: You map to spark change. Your routes emphasize leverage points and minimal moves that flip states, so the system reorients with a small, decisive nudge.
variants.Origin: You saw endless tinkering waste time. You learned to pick pathways that hit critical mass quickly and force a new trajectory.
variants.Inner Conflict: You sometimes pick disruptive paths that shock the system to life at a cost. The ethical and practical trade-offs are ever-present.
variants.Field Presence: Teams accelerate when they follow your levered routes; inertia breaks and motion follows. Risk is higher, reward often outsized. Signal: Levered routes ignite.

variants.title: Navigator × Vessel
variants.Psychological Profile: You map by craft. Your routes include quality gates and refinement points; you care that the path produces durable, well-made outcomes, not just speed.
variants.Origin: You watched sloppy launches collapse under pressure. You learned to design routes that bake in quality so the outcome survives the first real test.
variants.Inner Conflict: You refine until the window passes. The tension is between craft and meeting the moment; sometimes the perfect route is too late.
variants.Field Presence: People trust the durability of outcomes that follow your routes. Your approach reduces rework, though it can feel slow to those chasing velocity. Signal: Crafted routes endure.
